## 🔹 1. Version Control System (VCS)

A **Version Control System** helps track and manage changes in source code over time.

### 📌 Why VCS?

* Track changes 📜
* Collaboration 🤝
* Branching & merging 🌿
* Version history 🕒
* Conflict resolution ⚔️
* Backup & recovery 💾

---

## 🔹 2. Types of VCS

### 🔸 Centralized VCS (CVCS)

* Example: SVN
* Single central server

### 🔸 Distributed VCS (DVCS)

* Example: Git
* Each developer has full copy

---

## 🔹 3. What is Git?

Git is a **distributed version control system** used to:

* Track code changes
* Collaborate with others
* Maintain project history

---

## 🔹 4. Git Workflow

```text
Working Directory → Staging Area → Local Repository → Remote Repository
```

### Flow:

* git add → staging
* git commit → local repo
* git push → remote repo

---

## 🔹 5. Important Git Commands

### 🔧 Setup

```bash
git --version
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"
```

---

### 📁 Basic Commands

```bash
git init
git add <file>
git add .
git status
git commit -m "message"
```

---

### 📊 Logs & Changes

```bash
git log
git log --oneline
git diff
```

---

### 🔄 Reset & Stash

```bash
git reset <commit-id>
git reset --hard <commit-id>
git stash
git stash pop
```

---

### 🌐 Remote Commands

```bash
git clone <repo-url>
git remote add origin <url>
git push origin main
git pull origin main
```

---

## 🔹 6. Git Internals

* `.git` folder → stores all history
* Commits → snapshot of project
* Staging area → temporary storage

---

## 🔹 7. Git Branching

Branching allows working on features independently.

### 📌 Commands:

```bash
git branch <branch-name>
git checkout <branch-name>
git checkout -b <branch-name>
```

---

## 🔹 8. Merging & Strategies

### 🔀 Merge

```bash
git checkout main
git merge <branch-name>
```

---

### 🔹 Squash Merge

* Combines multiple commits into one
* Cleaner history

```bash
git merge --squash <branch-name>
```

---

### 🔹 Rebase

* Keeps history linear
* Re-applies commits on top

```bash
git rebase main
```

---

## 🔹 9. Revert vs Reset

* `git revert` → creates new commit (safe)
* `git reset` → moves HEAD (dangerous)

---

## 🔹 10. GitHub

GitHub is a **cloud platform to store Git repositories**

### 📌 Benefits:

* Backup code
* Collaboration
* Project sharing

---

## 🔹 11. Open Source Contribution Flow

1. Fork repository
2. Clone repo
3. Add upstream
4. Make changes
5. Push changes
6. Create Pull Request

---

## 🧠 Key Learnings

* Git tracks changes efficiently
* Branching enables parallel development
* GitHub helps collaboration
* Open source workflow is essential

